    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St. Thomas</placeName> <date>Crev Shabbat Kovach</date></p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><date>June 30<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 5608 &#40;1848&#41;</date></p>
			<p>My dear friend</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">In the first place allow me to return<lb/> you many thanks for the very handsome form in which<lb/> the Road of faith has been printed and for the trouble you<lb/> took in superintending its execution&#44; also for the trans&#45;<lb/>mission of 75 copies for which you will be good enough<lb/> to make my <sic>acknoweldgements</sic> to our esteemed friend <persName>Miss<lb/> Gratz</persName>. If I knew in what manner I could make my humble<lb/> abilities to the parent Jewish Sunday School in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName><lb/> serviceable I <del>sh</del>would with much willingness undertake any<lb/> other little work that might advance Elementary religious<lb/> education&#44; so admirably begun and continued that Institution.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Herewith you will receive our new code of<lb/> Laws with instructions from <persName>Mr. Wolff</persName> how many are to be<lb/> printed. The written copy was done by a lad&#44; yet I hope the<lb/> writing is sufficiently intelligible for you and the printer. The<lb/> marginal notes are&#44; of course&#44; to be annexed. Have them<lb/> neatly done&#44; and have the goodness to use your excellent taste<lb/> and <sic>judgement</sic> in the typographical art&#44; for which you are<lb/> so deservedly celebrated.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I may say of these laws as <persName>Solon</persName> said of his&#59; they are not the best that could have been made&#44; but they are the best<lb/> adapted for the persons who are to be ruled by them. Many will per&#45;<lb/>haps astonish you&#44; but on due and mature deliberation&#44; I have no<lb/> hesitation in saying&#44; altho&#39; I am a party concerned&#44; that they and the<lb/> labor of much thought&#44; and have been framed to meet the exigencies<lb/> of a congregation so heterogeneously composed as that of <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Expedition is necessary in the printing of these laws<lb/> no doubt you will be able to forward them by the packet<lb/> which will sail from <placeName>New York</placeName> in <date>August</date>. If you do&#44; I shall<lb/> contrive to get you voted a piece of a plate&#44; until we can give<lb/> you something better.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I wrote you 2 months back by the Gt. Western.<lb/> Did you receive my letter&#63; Everything here looks gloomy<lb/> owing to recent events in <placeName>Europe</placeName> and the civil war in <placeName>Venezuela</placeName>&#59;<lb/> money has vanished&#44; for the last 6 months I have recd. no<lb/> salary and even the latter has been reduced to &#36;1000 p annum.<lb/> I am obliged to have recourse to school shop again&#44; but the<lb/> establishment has every appearance and prospect of success.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">My health is good&#44; better than it has been<lb/> for years past&#44; but <persName>Mrs. Nathan</persName>&#44; her mother&#44; and her aged Grand&#45;<lb/>parent are all unwell. Your&#39;s&#44; I hope&#44; is not suffering from<lb/> the summer heats.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Present <del>my</del> our best compliments and warmest<lb/> wishes to all our old friends. I long to see you and have a<lb/> few good chats with you and all those of whose kindness<lb/> we <del>I</del> entertain so lively and grateful a recollection. Congratulate<lb/> <persName>Miss Cousens</persName> for us&#44; as we understand she has been or is<lb/> about to be married. In haste</p>
          <p rend="indent(6)">Most truly yours</p>
          <p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">M N Nathan</persName></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          
